He graduated Higher Military Aviation School from [[Kharkiv]] (1967), [[Gagarin Air Force Academy]] in [[Moscow]] (1976) and the Police Academy in Moscow.\n\nDuring 1967-1984 he worked as aviation officer in the [[Soviet Army]], first as a pilot (1967), squadron commander (1976-1978) and then as deputy commander of joined troops (1978-1980). Becomes regimental commander (1980-1983), with 102 fighters under his direction and then deputy commander of the [[14th Army (Soviet Union)]] on aviation issues.\n\nIn 1984 was appointed deputy commander [[DOSAAF]] (Volunteer Society for Cooperation with the Army, Aviation, and Fleet) RSS Moldavia ([[Moldavian Soviet Socialist Republic]]), and the following year became commander of the Central Committee of [[DOSAAF]], holding this position until in 1990. He was promoted in October 1988 to the rank of General-Major of the Soviet Army aviation.\n\nIn 1990 he was appointed Chairman of Committee Supreme Soviet of RSS Moldavia for State Security and Military Affairs, and in September 1990 - a member of the Presidential Council of the Republic of [[Moldova]]. Between 1990-1992, General Ion Costa\u015f served as Minister of Internal Affairs in the Government of Moldova.\n\nState by Presidential Decree no. 20 of 5 February 1992, Division General Ion Costa\u015f was appointed as the first Minister of Defence of the Republic, but was dismissed (along with Anatol Plugaru, Security Minister) after Moldovan troops lost the fighting to restore part of Moldova [[Transnistria]] against Transnistrian paramilitary troops and 14th Russian Army, led by General [[Aleksandr Lebed]].\n\nHe was then appointed as military attache in Romania, where he was recalled in October 1993 and went into reserve.\n\nIon Costa\u015f was awarded the order \"Service in the armed forces of their native country\" grade III with 6 medals. On 24 February 2010, the Minister of Internal Affairs, General [[Victor Catan]], Gen. Ion Costa\u015f was decorated with \"The Cross of Merit\", the highest distinction of the MIA with occasion of celebrating of his birthday.\n\nAfter retiring from politics in 1993, Ion Costas has entered the business sector. He is currently the general manager of Crystal System, an international group specialized in Information Technology. He was previously a regional manager for Hewlett Packard and for the Petrom, a large Romanian oil company. He led the contingent of veterans of the [[Transnistrian War]] on [[Great National Assembly Square, Chi\u0219in\u0103u|Great National Assembly Square]] during the 2011 [[Chi\u0219in\u0103u Independence Day Parade]].<ref>https://gagauzinfo.md/top1/1389-v-kishineve-proshel-voennyjj-parad-po.html</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[War of Transnistria]]\n* [[Timeline of events in the War of Transnistria]]\n* [[1990 Moldovan parliamentary election|Moldovan parliamentary election from 1990]]\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|ru}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20100205143400/http://politicom.moldova.org/news/-199328-rus.html Online resource Moldova.org - \u0418\u043e\u043d \u041a\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0448: \"\u0411\u044b\u043b\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0430!\", \u0441\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0442\u0438\u044f 1990-1992 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430 \u0414\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435]\n\n{{Popular Front of Moldova}}\n{{Moldovan Parliament 1990-1994}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Costas, Ion}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Moldovan Ministers of Defense]]\n[[Category:Moldovan Ministers of the Interior]]\n[[Category:Moldovan MPs 1990\u20131994]]\n[[Category:Moldovan generals]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion_Costa%C8%99"}
